<HEADLINE>
2007 TAIWAN INTERNATIONAL MOTORCYCLE TRADE FAIR TO OPEN MAY 18
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April 13 (CNA) 04/13/07  18:43:24 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The 2007 Taiwan International Motorcycle Industry Show is
scheduled to take place May 18-20 at the Taipei World Trade
Center's Exhibition Hall 3, with some 160 exhibitors from Taiwan
and abroad presenting their latest motorbike models and
accessories.
</P>
<P>
According the organizer, the Taiwan External Trade Development
Council (TAITRA), the exhibitors will use 385 booths, an increase
of 25 percent over last year's exhibition.
</P>
<P>
These exhibitors include local agents of renowned motorcycle
brand names, such as Japan's Yamaha, Italy's Ducati, Bimota and
Piaggio, as well as suppliers of motorcycle parts and components
from Taiwan, China, Pakistan, India and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
TAITRA officials said that Germany's BMW Group and Austria's
Kiska, a design agency, will come to the show to look for
business partners in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
In addition to booths showcasing complete motorcycles, scooters,
parts, accessories, and production and inspection equipment, the
show will present 100 fancy, dressed-up motorcycles remodeled in
Taiwan in hopes of looking for buyers and promoting opportunities
for parts manufacturers to do remodeling jobs.
</P>
<P>
There will be four seminars at the exhibition site to help
participants in the show keep pace with new trends in the
motorcycle industry.
</P>
<P>
Gerald Kiska, chief executive officer of Kiska Design, will give
a lecture on "Motorcycle Design"; Chuck Crone, director of
special projects and sourced vehicles at America's Polaris Co.,
will speak on "Opportunities to Supply Major All-Terrain Vehicle
Manufacturers"; Jacques Compagne,  secretary-general of the
Association of the European Motorcycle Manufacturers, will talk
about "Motorcycle Market in the Europe"; George Lin, president of
Taiwan Golden Bee Co., will discuss "Global Opportunities for
Taiwan Motorcycle Industry."
</P>
